Vauxhall Insignia review
Andrew English ponders whether the changes to the 2014 model year Vauxhall Insignia go far enough.
4
Cosmetic changes to the 2014 model year Vauxhall Insignia include new bumpers, headlights and front grille By Andrew English
5:17PM BST 25 Sep 2013
Comments
I overheard a couple of colleagues talking about the discounts availabe on the Vauxhall Insignia recently. This 2009 Car of the Year is still doing good business, selling 32,610 in the UK last year, yet apparently they can be had for just four-figure sums. "Yeah, but it's an Insignia," said one as if that explained everything. The problem is that however well the Insignia drives, rides and sells, people still see it as a prestige-free repmobile. In the UK, where at least 80 per cent of the 167,000 Insignias sold since 2009 have gone to business customers, Vauxhall doesn't do itself any favours by allowing sub-10-grand new cars on the forecourt. It's Britain's fleet market which distorts and corrupts values. Even BMW, which sells more of its 3-series models than Vauxhall sells Insignias, is not immune to discounting. As Stuart Harris, Vauxhall marketing expert, says: "the premium makers have now got a taste for volume, but sometimes that's a bitter taste."
Related Articles
Opel Monza concept at Frankfurt
10 Sep 2013
Why Vauxhall's Mini misses its mark
26 Aug 2013
Driven: Vauxhall Cascada
24 Mar 2013
Long-term review: Vauxhall Insignia Sports Tourer 2.0 CDTi
06 Dec 2013
Driving a Vauxhall 30/98
01 Apr 2013
Driven: Vauxhall Mokka Tech Line 1.6
15 Mar 2013
The facelifted Insignia is on sale now for delivery in October as a five-door hatchback, four-door saloon and "Sports Tourer" estate, with the range priced from £16,279 to £29,329. Scope those new headlamps, grille and more coherent brightwork. The Insignia was one of the first Vauxhalls to benefit from design chief Mark Adams' new-form philosophy and this update is designed to make it look lower and wider. All the sheet metal is carried over, as is the underbody, but the tailgate is new. I used to like the old model with its pert tail and although the facelift makes it look more modern, it's also slightly fussy. Step inside and you can see why you might learn to love a non-premium car for reasons other than price. Unlike German rivals, Vauxhall/Opel is neither in thrall to the Apple Corporation, nor cowering like ignorant medieval villagers from the voodoo technology of touchscreens. The dash is simple but well finished, the combined digital/analogue instrument binnacle works well and the large optional touchscreen, with its accompanying touch pad is both clearly marked and relatively easy to use. There are simple icons you can move around the screen, or if you use two fingers on the touch pad it will scroll, three fingers and you access a favourites menu, including phone numbers, tunes, destinations or a selection of 'curated' apps. The software isn't the world's most straightforward, but fiddling and Anglo Saxon gets you there in the end and if you are of the Luddite persuasion, you can download a smart phone handbook app, which you point at the switch in question for a tutorial. What's clear here is that Vauxhall has grown up. The colour choices are warm and welcoming, the fit and finish is as good as anything from Audi or BMW. The plain, dark plastics lovely to touch and the contrasting nappa leather is a delight. Remember, though, that this is a fleet car, and that leather costs an extra £3,000. I wasn't convinced by the standard seats, but the optional £1,149 orthopedically designed driver's seat is one of the most comfortable chairs you'll find outside of a Volvo. There's plenty of room in the back for two six-foot adults and the boot is a healthy 530 litres. Even this simplified range is bewildering. The Insignia is available with four four-cylinder petrol engines and four diesel options, all variations of the same 2.0-litre, four-cylinder unit delivering power outputs of between 118bhp and 192bhp and CO2 emissions of between 99g/km and 125g/km. There's also a new 320bhp, 170mph 4x4 VXR model and a Country Tourer 4x4 estate. Both cars use twin electronically controlled Haldex clutch packs, the first to direct up to 40 per cent of the engine's torque to the rear wheels, the second to direct torque to the rear wheel with the most grip. The Country Tourer arrives in January, with prices starting at £25,349, and the VXR will cost from £29,749. We concentrated on the £21,159, 161bhp diesel, which will occupy about 30 per cent of sales. It returns 65.7mpg on the Combined cycle, emits 114g/km of CO2, and attracts 17 per cent benefit-in-kind tax. Of six basic trim levels we chose SRI, which comes with that ergonomic driver's seat as standard, but not the £1,200 large touchscreen. It's quick enough to make a satisfying drive, but economical (we managed 49.6mpg). Refinement at speed is good and noise levels are low, but there's an annoying vibration as the engine revs drop towards 1,000rpm, so you need to row it along below 45mph. Not really a problem, because although the gearlever is a monstrosity, the change quality is precise, if a little stiff. Vauxhall/Opel engineers have worked hard at the suspension. Front MacPherson struts have specially shaped compliant top mounts to help the wheels roll over bumps and potholes. New bushes and dampers are fitted all round and the multi-link independent rear has new springs. The suspension was honed in Britain as well as Germany and it shows. A week before the German elections, driving the Insignia near Frankfurt was like driving through a party political broadcast, all corners obscured by grinning images of politicians bearing a startling resemblance to either Thelma from Scooby Doo or the Hoff. Eventually we found a bumpy, twisting road and could clearly determine that the Insignia's ride is more compliant and comfortable. Vauxhall says the handling hasn't been compromised in the process and we'd agree. There's a lightness to the major controls and a mostly progressive build up of steering loads. The electronically assisted system can be inconsistent, however, and has an over-centre feel particularly in the Sport mode of the £790 Flexride system. There's also not much feedback through the wheel even when pressing on, which inhibits spirited driving. That said, the chassis is well balanced and understeer and body roll are reasonably well controlled. So, good just got better. The Insignia is still a great car and it seems a pity we all spend our money on other German cars - with flashier badges - since they're not necessarily better. VAUXHALL INSIGNIA
Engine/transmission: 1956cc four-cylinder turbodiesel with double overhead camshafts and four valves per cylinder. Six-speed manual transmission (optional six-speed auto) driving the front wheels (opt 4x4 system) Price/on sale: From £16,279 to £29,329. As tested in SRI 163PS CDTi form, £21,159. On sale November Power/torque: 161bhp @ 4,000rpm, 258lb ft @ 1,750rpm. Top speed: 136mph Acceleration: 0-62mph 9.5sec. Fuel economy: 52.3mpg/65.7mpg EU Urban/Combined. On test 49.6mpg. CO2 emissions: 114g/km VED band: C - £0 for the first year, £30 thereafter Verdict: Good just got better, with an improved ride quality, classier cabin, a bit of felt-tip fandango on the exterior and quieter high speed running. Not the greatest driving machine, but comfortable and competent. Telegraph rating: Four out of five stars. RIVALS
Ford Mondeo (from £15,995) The blue oval's ship of the line is getting rather long in the tooth, with a much delayed replacement due at the end of next year. It still makes a fine drive, with better handling than most, but the ride is showing its age and we're waiting for some new engines. Don't pay retail prices... Peugeot 508 (from £19,105) This is the first of the new-look Peugeots under design head Gilles Vidal. It's handsome with a lovely and comfortable cabin, although some of the fleet-friendly driveline and suspension combinations don't sparkle. Avoid the ponderous semi-automatic transmission. Hyundai i40 (from £18,765) Well made and stylish, and there's the benefit of a five-year warranty, but not quite as plush or as good to drive as the best. Worth consideration, though. Vauxhall
